defaultBackgrounddefaultThe C
defaultonfederation of UK Coal Producers (Coalpro)
default represents the 
defaultcoal
default ind
defaultustry within the United Kingdom, our members produce 95% of the 
defaultcoal
default mined in the UK from both deep and surface mines
default. The UK 
defaultCoal 
defaultIndustry
default produced 16.3Mt in 2012 around 90% of which was sold into power stations in the UK.
default 
defaultCoalpro is a member of the CBI M
defaultinerals Group.
defaultThese sales would otherwise be replaced by imported coal as almost 50Mt was consumed by UK power stations in 2012. The industry employed just over 6,000 people to produce this output and although this has declined in 2013 following the closu
defaultre of Maltby Colliery and Daw Mill Colliery and the collapse of two of the companies operating surface mines in Scotland we expect the figure to be well in excess of 4,500 direct employees by the early part of 2014 as some the operations in Scotland re-com
defaultmence production. In addition to the power station market coal is an essential and affordable fuel for households which are off the gas grid (estimated to be 6 million homes) and of course is used by some key industries such as cement and sugar processing.
default 
defaultOne industry which has to use coal is steel-making as the carbon in the coal and the iron ore chemically bond in the blast furnace, in this case there is no alternative fuel and although the majority of the coal used in this process in the UK is imported
default there are some coals which are suitable in parts of the UK, notably North-East England and South Wales. Tata steel have a policy of preferring to purchase these coals when they are available, as they provide secure and local supplies with reduced costs of
default transportation both in fuel and emissions. The suitability depends on the characteristics of each individual coal seam in the mine and the mine must have other markets for the other coal seams it mines (principally power generation).   
defaultExecutive defaultSummarydefaultQuestionsdefault&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultCoal mining in the UK contributes both financially and socially on a national and local level. Coal deposits are present in some of the more economically deprived areas of Scotland , Northern England and South Wales and the mines, whether surface or underg
defaultround,  predominantly employ local labour. The cost of regenerating these areas after deep mine closure both in social and economic terms is well known to Government. In addition, local haulage and small engineering businesses depend on the coal mines, bot
defaulth surface and underground, for a large proportion of their turnover. 
defaultA large proportion of rail freight traffic is from the transport of bulk materials, c35% in 2010 of all freight was the haulage of coal to power stations, UK produced coal accounts for a
defaultbout one third of this total. Track access fees for these movements make up a significant portion of Network Rail’s income.
